liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NSW assistant commissioner Tony Cooke said one person carrying a flag was arrested at at Sydney Town Hall last night. He said the person was removed for their own safety and released. Assistant Commissioner Cooke defended advice from police for Israel supporters to stay away from the protest and denied he had any conversation with the New South Wales Police Minister about operational matters related to the protest. "This is very clearly an emotive issue across community," he said. "We continue to work across all communities. Absolutely. This is New South Wales. "We do not expect people to bring conflict from other places to the streets of Sydney and it will not be tolerated." He said an operation had been established to investigate what happened and identify people who committed offences. "I'm very disappointed in the strongest possible terms that people saw fit to utilise flares and what not," he said. "However, I can tell you the entirerally and footage was covered by CCTV footage." liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NSW Premier Chris Minns says he was horrified by the protest at the Sydney Opera House last night. "To celebrate what's happened in the Middle East in the last 48 hours is abhorrent," he told ABC News Breakfast. "I can't understand why the protest went ahead in any event. "The position of the New South Wales government is unambiguously clear — we lit up the Opera House in solidarity with the people of Israel and the Jewish community in New South Wales because we were as horrified as the rest of the community at the indiscriminate slaughter that took place in Israel." He said the situation was "obviously intolerable" for the Jewish community of New South Wales. "We cannot have a situation where members of the Jewish community feel that they can't and are being told not to participate in their city," he said. He said the decision to tell members of the Jewish community not to go to the Opera House was an "operational policing decision for the safety and security of the city". He said there were discussions happening between the government, police and the Jewish community. "The situation where they're told not to come into the city, despite it being an operational decision in a tight time frame, went ahead last night but that's intolerable for the future, and I know New South Wales police are talking with that community today and changes will be made." Watch the full interview below.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Josephine Lim Foreign Minister Penny Wong told ABC Radio Adelaide that Australia hasn't been asked to provide defence support. "What we are doing is engaging with Israelis but also, as per their request, with others in the region because what we don’t want to see is this escalate any further," she said, adding she spoke with the Jordanian foreign minister last night. Responding to criticisms that her statement yesterday was a "half-hearted response", Ms Wong said she "unequivocally" condemned the Hamas attack and called for the protection of civilian lives. "I would have thought that was a pretty unremarkable thing for Australia to call for, we always seek that as a nation, we always called for civilian lives to be protected," she said. "My response would be, what would the alternative be? "Australia calls for hostages to be returned. We condemn Hamas's abhorrent attacks. We stand with Israel and we recognise its rights to defend itself."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wong says she 'unequivocally' condemns Hamas attack after criticism of 'half-hearted' response

children.content: Reporting by Josephine Lim
Foreign Minister Penny Wong told ABC Radio Adelaide that Australia hasn't been asked to provide defence support.

"What we are doing is engaging with Israelis but also, as per their request, with others in the region because what we don’t want to see is this escalate any further," she said, adding she spoke with the Jordanian foreign minister last night.
Responding to criticisms that her statement yesterday was a "half-hearted response", Ms Wong said she "unequivocally" condemned the Hamas attack and called for the protection of civilian lives.
"I would have thought that was a pretty unremarkable thing for Australia to call for, we always seek that as a nation, we always called for civilian lives to be protected," she said.
"My response would be, what would the alternative be?
"Australia calls for hostages to be returned. We condemn Hamas's abhorrent attacks. We stand with Israel and we recognise its rights to defend itself."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Kimberley Price Collingwood captain Darcy Moore has come out in support of the Yes campaign ahead of this weekend's Voice referendum. It follows fellow sports star, Panthers NRL Premiership hero Nathan Cleary also announcing his support for a First Nations Voice to Parliament. A week after winning the AFL Premiership, Darcy Moore told RN Breakfast host Patricia Karvelas that despite what some people thought, sport and politics could mix. "I'll be voting yes. To me, I feel like it's an intuitive next step and seems to be an important and practical way to help Indigenous Australians," he said. "There are certainly people out there that want you to shut up and play sport, but we've seen all around the country, like with Nathan Cleary, athletes are human beings and citizens of the country too, so they can exercise their right and say what they want to say and they can do it in a really healthy way. "The argument around division … to my mind there is already advisory bodies for Indigenous Australians that have come and gone as governments have changed. The mechanism has kind of already existed anyway, so by making it sort of permanent in the constitution, it's just locking it in. So in that way it's not anything new." Listen to the full interview below.

Panthers NRL Premiership hero Nathan Cleary
also announcing his support for a First Nations Voice to Parliament.
A week after winning the AFL Premiership, Darcy Moore told
RN Breakfast host Patricia Karvelas
that despite what some people thought, sport and politics could mix.
"I'll be voting yes. To me, I feel like it's an intuitive next step and seems to be an important and practical way to help Indigenous Australians," he said.

"There are certainly people out there that want you to shut up and play sport, but we've seen all around the country, like with Nathan Cleary, athletes are human beings and citizens of the country too, so they can exercise their right and say what they want to say and they can do it in a really healthy way.

"The argument around division … to my mind there is already advisory bodies for Indigenous Australians that have come and gone as governments have changed. The mechanism has kind of already existed anyway, so by making it sort of permanent in the constitution, it's just locking it in. So in that way it's not anything new."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Speaking on ABC News Breakfast this morning, chairman of the Aboriginal Land Council of Tasmania Michael Mansell said that "saving a miracle" the Voice to Parliament is "dead in the water". "The referendum will be defeated on Saturday," he said. "The prime minister has said that he's not going to legislate after the referendum for a Voice to Parliament and so what we need to start doing is looking at, well, from Sunday onwards, where do we go? "We know that the prime minister has said he's going to implement the Uluru Statement in full, and we also know that there are 19 Closing The Gap targets that haven't been fulfilled, so there's plenty of work to do." Mr Mansell said that if the Voice to Parliament doesn't go through, he expects advocacy to continue. "I think rather than the prime minister allow the Yes camp to walk away bitterly disappointed with the outcome, feeling completely empty and hopeless because the whole thing came to nothing, [he] is going to have to offer that group some way to use their energies in the next 12 months."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Aboriginal leader Michael Mansell says Voice 'dead in the water'

Speaking on ABC News Breakfast this morning, chairman of the Aboriginal Land Council of Tasmania
Michael Mansell
said that "saving a miracle" the Voice to Parliament is "dead in the water".
"The referendum will be defeated on Saturday," he said.

"The prime minister has said that he's not going to legislate after the referendum for a Voice to Parliament and so what we need to start doing is looking at, well, from Sunday onwards, where do we go?

"We know that the prime minister has said he's going to implement the Uluru Statement in full, and we also know that there are 19 Closing The Gap targets that haven't been fulfilled, so there's plenty of work to do."
Mr Mansell said that if the Voice to Parliament doesn't go through, he expects advocacy to continue.

"I think rather than the prime minister allow the Yes camp to walk away bitterly disappointed with the outcome, feeling completely empty and hopeless because the whole thing came to nothing, [he] is going to have to offer that group some way to use their energies in the next 12 months."
